s between tribal elites and the royal family explain, to a large extent, the extraordinary resilience of Hashemite rule in Jordan and the country's relative stability. Mithqal al-Fayiz's life and work as a shaykh offer a notable individual story, as well as a unique window into the history, society, and politics of Jordan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBedouinszJordanvBiography. 0aStatesmenzJordanvBiography. 0aTribal governmentzJordanxHistoryy20th century. 4aBedouin. 4aBritish Empire. 4aJordan. 4aOttoman Empire. 4aSyria. 4aTransjordan. 4acolonialism. 4ashaykh. 4astate formation. 4atribes. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479934840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799348.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles